Hi Sherry,


Please perform the follow steps and upload the resulting Artifacts:

Enable Debug Logging
From the NEA Console > Settings > Application
Set Log Level to Debug
Rerun jobs that are failing to collect logs in full detail. Return Log level to warning afterwards.
[cid:image001.png@01DB2F69.D96D6BA0]

Please provide logs from the following locations:
Enterprise Auditor Console: %SAInstallDir%SADatabaseLogsApplication

Export of Job(s) – note jobs may be nested under multiple Groups:
Right click on the Job or Job Group experiencing problems and select Export. This creates .zip file containing all logs and configuration settings of your jobs that we can import and review.
[cid:image002.png@01DB2F69.D96D6BA0]

From the Job Status Export the Messages Table, CSV is preferred:
[cid:image003.png@01DB2F69.D96D6BA0]

Upload these artifacts by logging to the customer portal:

Hello Sherry,

Today we:

We checked the existing Proxy server defined in the job and found out that mentioned server didn't had the Proxy applet installed. Hi Sherry, Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. 



Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.


[cid:image007.png@01DB2F69.D96D6BA0]


2. In the opened window, click on Configure.

[cid:image008.png@01DB2F69.D96D6BA0]

Hi Sherry, Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. 



Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.


[cid:image018.png@01DB2F6B.F6623900]


2. In the opened window, click on Configure.

[cid:image019.png@01DB2F6B.F6623900]


3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.

Have a great day!

Hello Sherry,

This issue usually occurs to duplicate certificates in the Proxy Server and NEA console. To resolve this issue please follow this KB article:

Error: Cannot Initialize Scan with Proxy Host in Enterprise Auditor 11.6<https://urldefense.com/v3/__https:/helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/z-kb-articles-salesforce/page/kA0Qk0000000WSvKAM.html__;!!Kjv0uj3L4nM6H-I!huZFfGkl9rOnRbXFtgxQDLnzAE35Nty0DMDZzCfUyreVpYK2cRcav7mGdhWR2SyL3FUSDtmxDKMB6cp85w$>

Get-CimInstance -Class Win32_Product |Where-Object {($_.Name -Like "Stealth*" -or $_.Name -like "Netwrix*" -or $_.Name -like "Postg*" -or ` $_.Name -like "Python*")} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

Enable Debug Logging

Set Log Level to Debug

Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.
 



 



2. In the opened window, click on Configure.




 



3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.



Have a great day!

Hello Sherry,

This issue usually occurs to duplicate certificates in the Proxy Server and NEA console. To resolve this issue please follow this KB article:

Error: Cannot Initialize Scan with Proxy Host in Enterprise Auditor 11.6

However, if the issue is not resolved, please share the following information to help me streamline the troubleshooting process and resolve your issue more efficiently:

What is the impact of the issue on your business? 
Who is affected by this issue? 
What steps to troubleshoot the issue have already been taken? 
What are you trying to do or accomplish? 
Is this a new configuration, data collection or report? 
If no, has anything changed in your environment since the last time it worked? 
When did this issue start?  
What are the steps to reproduce? 
What software is currently installed - run this command from an admin PowerShell prompt:

Get-CimInstance -Class Win32_Product |Where-Object {($_.Name -Like "Stealth*" -or $_.Name -like "Netwrix*" -or $_.Name -like "Postg*" -or ` $_.Name -like "Python*")} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.
 



 



2. In the opened window, click on Configure.




 



3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.



Have a great day!

Hello Sherry,

Thank you for taking the time to meet today.

Today we:
troubleshooted the issue you were facing when running FSAC scan against a Nasuni appliance. We checked the existing Proxy server defined in the job and found out that mentioned server didn't had the Proxy applet installed. Hi Sherry, Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. 



Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.


[cid:image009.png@01DB2F6E.44300F70]


2. In the opened window, click on Configure.

[cid:image010.png@01DB2F6E.44300F70]


3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.

Have a great day!

Error: Cannot Initialize Scan with Proxy Host in Enterprise Auditor 11.6<https://urldefense.com/v3/__https:/helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/z-kb-articles-salesforce/page/kA0Qk0000000WSvKAM.html__;!!Kjv0uj3L4nM6H-I!huZFfGkl9rOnRbXFtgxQDLnzAE35Nty0DMDZzCfUyreVpYK2cRcav7mGdhWR2SyL3FUSDtmxDKMB6cp85w$>

Get-CimInstance -Class Win32_Product |Where-Object {($_.Name -Like "Stealth*" -or $_.Name -like "Netwrix*" -or $_.Name -like "Postg*" -or ` $_.Name -like "Python*")} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

Please perform the follow steps and upload the resulting Artifacts:

Enable Debug Logging
From the NEA Console > Settings > Application
Set Log Level to Debug
Rerun jobs that are failing to collect logs in full detail. Return Log level to warning afterwards.

Enterprise Auditor Console: %SAInstallDir%SADatabaseLogsApplication

Hi Sherry, Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. 



 


Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.
 



 



2. In the opened window, click on Configure.




 



3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.



Have a great day!

Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.


[cid:image010.png@01DB2F70.1876C0C0]


2. In the opened window, click on Configure.

[cid:image011.png@01DB2F70.1876C0C0]


3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.

Have a great day!

Hello Sherry,

Thank you for taking the time to meet today.

Today we:
troubleshooted the issue you were facing when running FSAC scan against a Nasuni appliance. We checked the existing Proxy server defined in the job and found out that mentioned server didn't had the Proxy applet installed. During the discussion, you mentioned that you were using a different proxy server for FSAA scans. We used that proxy server in StealthAudit console and the FSAC scan started to run. You also mentioned that Windows Host mentioned in the same job was not functional. We assigned permissions using this KB article:

https://helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/EnterpriseAuditor_11.6/page/Content/EnterpriseAuditor/Requirements/Solutions/FileSystem/ProxyModeServicePermissions.htm

Since the job was taking time to run, we agreed that you will let it run and let me know about the status.

Our next steps are:

Monitor the job and let me know if there is any error.

follow up with you tomorrow and share a meeting schedule if required.

Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.
 



 



2. In the opened window, click on Configure.




 



3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.



Have a great day!

Hi Sherry, Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. 



Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.


[cid:image010.png@01DB2F71.28331D50]


2. In the opened window, click on Configure.

[cid:image011.png@01DB2F71.28331D50]


3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.

Have a great day!

Hello Sherry,

Thank you for contacting Netwrix Technical Support. I am Saqib and I am happy to assist you with this case.

This issue usually occurs to duplicate certificates in the Proxy Server and NEA console. To resolve this issue please follow this KB article:

Error: Cannot Initialize Scan with Proxy Host in Enterprise Auditor 11.6<https://urldefense.com/v3/__https:/helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/z-kb-articles-salesforce/page/kA0Qk0000000WSvKAM.html__;!!Kjv0uj3L4nM6H-I!huZFfGkl9rOnRbXFtgxQDLnzAE35Nty0DMDZzCfUyreVpYK2cRcav7mGdhWR2SyL3FUSDtmxDKMB6cp85w$>

However, if the issue is not resolved, please share the following information to help me streamline the troubleshooting process and resolve your issue more efficiently:

What is the impact of the issue on your business?
Who is affected by this issue?
What steps to troubleshoot the issue have already been taken?
What are you trying to do or accomplish?
Is this a new configuration, data collection or report?
If no, has anything changed in your environment since the last time it worked?
When did this issue start?
What are the steps to reproduce?
What software is currently installed - run this command from an admin PowerShell prompt:

Get-CimInstance -Class Win32_Product |Where-Object {($_.Name -Like "Stealth*" -or $_.Name -like "Netwrix*" -or $_.Name -like "Postg*" -or ` $_.Name -like "Python*")} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

Please perform the follow steps and upload the resulting Artifacts:

Enable Debug Logging
From the NEA Console > Settings > Application
Set Log Level to Debug
Rerun jobs that are failing to collect logs in full detail. Return Log level to warning afterwards.
[cid:image004.png@01DB2F71.28331D50]

Please provide logs from the following locations:
Enterprise Auditor Console: %SAInstallDir%SADatabaseLogsApplication

Export of Job(s) – note jobs may be nested under multiple Groups:
Right click on the Job or Job Group experiencing problems and select Export. This creates .zip file containing all logs and configuration settings of your jobs that we can import and review.
[cid:image005.png@01DB2F71.28331D50]

From the Job Status Export the Messages Table, CSV is preferred:

verified and discussed the errors you were observing in the FSAC System Scan Job and FSAC Bulk Import Job. We also saw a warning related to VSS in the StealthAudit Console. Since StealthAudit does not process VSS, we disabled the VSS scanning in Stealthbits Activity Monitor. Windows Host

Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.
 



 



2. In the opened window, click on Configure.




 



3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.



Have a great day!

Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.
 



 



2. In the opened window, click on Configure.




 



3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.



Have a great day!

Get-CimInstance -Class Win32_Product |Where-Object {($_.Name -Like "Stealth*" -or $_.Name -like "Netwrix*" -or $_.Name -like "Postg*" -or ` $_.Name -like "Python*")} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.
 



 



2. In the opened window, click on Configure.

4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Hi Sherry, Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. 



Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.


[cid:image012.png@01DB3451.889345F0]


2. In the opened window, click on Configure.

[cid:image013.png@01DB3451.889345F0]


3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.

Have a great day!

Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.
 



 



2. In the opened window, click on Configure.




 



3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.
 



 



2. In the opened window, click on Configure.




 



3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.



Have a great day!

Saqib Sharif
Technical Support Engineer

Hello Sherry,

This issue usually occurs to duplicate certificates in the Proxy Server and NEA console. To resolve this issue please follow this KB article:

Error: Cannot Initialize Scan with Proxy Host in Enterprise Auditor 11.6

However, if the issue is not resolved, please share the following information to help me streamline the troubleshooting process and resolve your issue more efficiently:

What is the impact of the issue on your business? 
Who is affected by this issue? 
What steps to troubleshoot the issue have already been taken? 
What are you trying to do or accomplish? 
Is this a new configuration, data collection or report? 
If no, has anything changed in your environment since the last time it worked? 
When did this issue start?  
What are the steps to reproduce? 
What software is currently installed - run this command from an admin PowerShell prompt:

Get-CimInstance -Class Win32_Product |Where-Object {($_.Name -Like "Stealth*" -or $_.Name -like "Netwrix*" -or $_.Name -like "Postg*" -or ` $_.Name -like "Python*")} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

Please perform the follow steps and upload the resulting Artifacts:

Enable Debug Logging
From the NEA Console > Settings > Application
Set Log Level to Debug
Rerun jobs that are failing to collect logs in full detail. Return Log level to warning afterwards.


Please provide logs from the following locations: 
Enterprise Auditor Console: %SAInstallDir%SADatabaseLogsApplication 

Export of Job(s) – note jobs may be nested under multiple Groups:
Right click on the Job or Job Group experiencing problems and select Export. This creates .zip file containing all logs and configuration settings of your jobs that we can import and review.


From the Job Status Export the Messages Table, CSV is preferred:

Hi Sherry, Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. 



 


Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.
 



 



2. In the opened window, click on Configure.




 



3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.



Have a great day!

Hi Sherry, Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. 



Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.


[cid:8d376049-49db-4398-b3c1-43d0ced96d79@Image_11_]


2. In the opened window, click on Configure.

[cid:2407508a-9cbb-4e24-b572-c541ccc94200@Image_12_]


3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.

Have a great day!

Hi Sherry, Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. 



 


Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.
 



 



2. In the opened window, click on Configure.




 



3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.



Have a great day!

Get-CimInstance -Class Win32_Product |Where-Object {($_.Name -Like "Stealth*" -or $_.Name -like "Netwrix*" -or $_.Name -like "Postg*" -or ` $_.Name -like "Python*")} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.
 



 



2. In the opened window, click on Configure.




 



3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.



Have a great day!

Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.


[cid:image012.png@01DB39AB.65B679D0]


2. In the opened window, click on Configure.

[cid:image013.png@01DB39AB.65B679D0]


3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.

Have a great day!

Hello Sherry,

Thank you for contacting Netwrix Technical Support. I am Saqib and I am happy to assist you with this case.

This issue usually occurs to duplicate certificates in the Proxy Server and NEA console. To resolve this issue please follow this KB article:

Error: Cannot Initialize Scan with Proxy Host in Enterprise Auditor 11.6<https://urldefense.com/v3/__https:/helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/z-kb-articles-salesforce/page/kA0Qk0000000WSvKAM.html__;!!Kjv0uj3L4nM6H-I!huZFfGkl9rOnRbXFtgxQDLnzAE35Nty0DMDZzCfUyreVpYK2cRcav7mGdhWR2SyL3FUSDtmxDKMB6cp85w$>

TextBody:
Hello Sherry,

I am glad that we were able to get your issue resolved. The following is a summary of the ticket for your records.

Symptom
You were observing an error with FSAC scan "Cannot Initialize Scan with Proxy Host Supplied ....". Later on, you saw a warning message with the FSAC Bulk Import job that there is no data to be imported.

Resolution
The proxy host supplied did not have the FSAA_Proxy.exe installed. When we selected a different proxy server, the error was gone and the scan was running fine. However, later you installed the FSAA_Proxy executable on the first host. The next error we saw was a warning message from the FSAC Bulk Import job. We discussed that the FSAC Scan Job must always be followed by the FSAC Bulk Import job. Otherwise, the data will not be imported for viewing. We also modified settings in Netwrix Activity Monitor to exclude VSS for a host so that warning messages would go away.

Following this email, you will receive an automated confirmation that the case is closed, along with the ability to re-open the case if any related errors return. In addition, you will also receive a separate email with a survey where you can let us know how we did. Feel free to leave any feedback via the survey link!

Have a great day!

Saqib Sharif
Technical Support Engineer

Hi Sherry,

Proxy server is the Windows Server which has FSAA proxy executable installed. This server is instructed by Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (StealthAudit) to collect logs on behalf of NEA server and once collected, send them to NEA server. You can verify if you have assigned any proxy server in the FSAC job settings. Please follow these steps to identify:

1. Navigate to the FSAC job -> Configure -> Queries and then click on Query Properties.
 



 



2. In the opened window, click on Configure.




 



3. In the next window, navigate to applet settings and see if you have selected the option "Require Applet to be running as a service on target".
4. In the left pane, click on Scan Server settings. In here, if you have a value set in "Specific Remote Server" or ""Specific Remote Servers by Host Lists".

If in step 3 and 4, you have values set as mentioned then you are using a proxy server. The proxy server is defined in step 4.

Let me know if you need further information or assistance.



Have a great day!
